We live in challenging times.

Have you ever wondered when you can contribute to solving the problems we are facing and make an impact? You don’t have to be brilliant, rich, or powerful - you, as a student, can take action for impact! In this workshop, we will start with a presentation by Prof. Goh about the work she has been doing in her research group, and how it has led to impact. She will then guide the workshop participants in identifying problems, and coming up with ideas on how to solve them. This could be your opportunity to be inspired to take action! Networking and discussions over refreshments will follow.

Prof. Goh is a professor of Chemistry, with cross-appointments in Materials Science & Engineering, Chemical Engineering & Applied Chemistry, Management & Innovation, and Medical Science. Her research interest spans nanoscience, interfacial phenomena, medical devices and technology for low resource settings, and the translation of knowledge from fundamental to applied. Together with her students, she co-founded several science-based startup companies that aim to make a better world (including Vive Crop Protection and Pueblo Science). She founded the Impact Centre, a unit for bringing science to society, developed entrepreneurship training programs and mentored over 150 startups. She has led numerous workshops internationally to help create and refine ideas in order to reach implementable solutions.

Introducing the speakers for our Explore Research Seminar: meet Dr. Dinesh Christendat!

Dr. Christendat is a full professor in Cell & Systems Biology at UTSG and serves as the Associate Chair for Undergraduate Studies. He earned his Ph.D. in September 1998 from the Department of Chemistry/Biochemistry at Concordia University in Montreal, Canada, under the guidance of Dr. Joanne Turnbull. His doctoral research primarily investigated the mechanistic aspects of E. coli Chorismate Mutase – Prephenate Dehydrogenase.
Dr. Christendat’s research interests span several areas, including Bioinformatics/Computational Biology, Metabolomics, Microbiology, Molecular Biology, Plant Biology, and Structural Biology. His current research focuses on investigating the regulation of central metabolites synthesized through the shikimate pathway in plants. He aims to uncover the biological cues involved in pathway regulation and enhance the biosynthesis of specific central metabolites, particularly those with nutritional importance.

Introducing the speakers for our Explore Research Seminar: meet Dr. Cynthia Goh!

Dr. Cynthia Goh is a Professor of Chemistry at UofT. She is the founder of the Impact Centre, which is an institute that aims to bring science to society, and was the inaugural Academic Director of University of Toronto Entrepreneurship. Her research interest centers on molecules that have an impact on nanotechnology, biomaterials, and biodiagnostics. Her research has led to 8 science-based companies, which she has co-founded with her students, including Pueblo Science. In 2003 she originated Entrepreneurship101, an introduction for students who want to be entrepreneurs. In 2010 she founded Techno, a training program for scientists/engineers who want to create science-based companies; this program led to 150+ student-led start-ups based on university research. Dr Goh’s current work involves applications of nanomaterials to health and environmental issues, and building community-based innovation systems in Canada and in the Philippines.

🎓🔬 Unlock Your Research Potential at UofT! 📚💡

Attention all undergraduates! Are you eager to dive into research but unsure where to start? Pueblo Science is hosting a virtual Discover Research event on Zoom this Monday, February 26th, at 5 pm.

This informational event will cover all the steps to secure a research opportunity, including:

1. Learning about the research opportunities UofT offers, such as ROPs, research-based courses, and volunteer positions.
2. Crafting a compelling email to professors. Professors will provide tips and tricks for writing personalized emails that highlight why you're a great fit for their research team.
3. Participating in a Q&A session to address any questions you may have!

🌟 Register for this event through the link in our bio or by scanning the QR code!
